title: 3I/ATLAS: Is This New Image The Proof We've Been Waiting For?
text:

The footage reveals a sleek, metallic, elongated structure glowing with evenly spaced lights, nothing like anything naturally formed.

Soon after, Dr. Avi Loeb reignited the debate, suggesting 3I/ATLASâ€™s trajectory could allow it to perform an Oberth maneuverâ€”a rare, high-efficiency acceleration that spacecraft use by diving near the Sun. Days later, amateur astronomer Tiago (Dobsonian Power) captured his own verified image, showing the same object at NASAâ€™s predicted coordinates: a bright, shield-like front facing the Sun, no tail, and no sign of normal cometary activity.

Is 3I/ATLAS just another interstellar cometâ€”or something far more advanced?
In this two-hour deep dive, we unravel the scientific evidence, the viral â€œleak,â€ and the mind-blowing possibility that 3I/ATLAS could be an engineered craft using the Sun for propulsion.

text:

title: Cosmic Dawn (NASA+ Original Documentary)
text:
What does it take to gaze through time to our universeâ€™s very first stars, galaxies, and light? â€œCosmic Dawn: The Untold Story of the James Webb Space Telescope,â€ a NASA+ documentary, takes you behind the scenes of Webbâ€™s journey, through the eyes of the dreamers who made it possible.

The documentary brings viewers on an unprecedented journey through Webbâ€™s delicate assembly, rigorous testing, and triumphant launch, showcasing the sheer complexity and breathtaking risks involved in creating a telescope capable of peering billions of years into the past. Follow the telescope from an idea developed at NASAâ€™s Goddard Space Flight Center all the way to the launchpad in French Guiana, with never-before-seen footage captured by the Webb film crew offering intimate access to the challenges and triumphs along the way.

title: NASA | A Year in the Life of Earth's CO2
text:
An ultra-high-resolution NASA computer model has given scientists a stunning new look at how carbon dioxide in the atmosphere travels around the globe.

Plumes of carbon dioxide in the simulation swirl and shift as winds disperse the greenhouse gas away from its sources. The simulation also illustrates differences in carbon dioxide levels in the northern and southern hemispheres and distinct swings in global carbon dioxide concentrations as the growth cycle of plants and trees changes with the seasons.

The carbon dioxide visualization was produced by a computer model called GEOS-5, created by scientists at NASA Goddard Space Flight Centerâ€™s Global Modeling and Assimilation Office.

The visualization is a product of a simulation called a â€œNature Run.â€ The Nature Run ingests real data on atmospheric conditions and the emission of greenhouse gases and both natural and man-made particulates. The model is then left to run on its own and simulate the natural behavior of the Earthâ€™s atmosphere. This Nature Run simulates January 2006 through December 2006.

While Goddard scientists worked with a â€œbetaâ€ version of the Nature Run internally for several years, they released this updated, improved version to the scientific community for the first time in the fall of 2014.

This video is public domain and can be downloaded at: http://svs.gsfc.nasa.gov/goto?11719
